   "source": [
    "# Application with new data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "26f27414",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This tutorial demonstrates how to identify spatial domains and how to train STAGATE in batches on new EEL FISH mouse brain data, as well as using Pysodb and STAGATE based on pyG (PyTorch Geometric) framework.\n",
    "\n",
    "Since the EEL FISH mouse brain has 127591 cells, each with 440 genes, this tutorial presents how to download data using Pysodb and also uses a batch training strategy to deal with large-scale data. \n",
    "\n",
    "A tutorial of a batch training strategy can be found at https://stagate.readthedocs.io/en/latest/T8_Batch.html"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2dea0e56-3693-4898-87f9-c33a3ad0b19f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Strategies for dividing subgraphs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "15653c58-3ddb-4a5d-a51f-814f0f416000",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Because we build the spatial network based on spatial location, our network can be directly divided into subgraphs in the following form."
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "# Import pysodb package\n",
    "# Pysodb is a Python package that provides a set of tools for working with SODB databases. \n",
    "# SODB is a format used to store data in memory-mapped files for efficient access and querying. \n",
    "# This package allows users to interact with SODB files using Python.\n",
    "import pysodb\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "d206c916",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Initialization\n",
    "sodb = pysodb.SODB()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "13b145e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "load experiment[mouse_brain] in dataset[Borm2022Scalable]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Define the name of the dataset_name and experiment_name\n",
    "dataset_name = 'Borm2022Scalable'\n",
    "experiment_name = 'mouse_brain'\n",
    "# Load a specific experiment\n",
    "# It takes two arguments: the name of the dataset and the name of the experiment to load.\n",
    "# Two arguments are available at https://gene.ai.tencent.com/SpatialOmics/.\n",
    "adata = sodb.load_experiment(dataset_name,experiment_name)"
   ]
  },

    "# Normalization\n",

   "source": [
    "# Assign spatial coordinates to adata.obs['X_coor'] and adata.obs['Y_coor']\n",
    "adata.obs['X_coor'] = adata.obsm['spatial'][:,0]\n",

    "# Create a PyTorch Geometric DataLoader object for loading and processing graph data\n",
    "from torch_geometric.loader import DataLoader\n",

    "# Create a PyTorch DataLoader object named \"loader\" that will iterate through the \"data_list\"\n",

   "source": [
    "# Hyper-parameters setting\n",
    "num_epoch = 500\n",
    "lr=0.001\n",
    "weight_decay=1e-4\n",
    "hidden_dims = [512, 30]"
   ]

   "source": [
    "# Train a STAGATE model \n",
    "model = STAGATE_pyG.STAGATE(hidden_dims = [data_list[0].x.shape[1]]+hidden_dims).to(device)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initializes an Adam optimizer with learning rate \"lr\" and weight decay \"weight_decay\" that will be used to update the parameters of the PyTorch model.\n",
    "optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=lr, weight_decay=weight_decay)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [
    "# Train a PyTorch model using mini-batch stochastic gradient descent with the Adam optimizer by iterating over the data loader \"loader\" for \"num_epoch\" epochs, computing the MSE loss between the predicted output \"out\" and the ground truth \"batch.x\", clipping the gradients to avoid exploding gradients, and updating the model parameters using the optimizer's step function.\n",
    "for epoch in tqdm(range(1, num_epoch+1)):\n",
    "    for batch in loader:\n",
    "        model.train()\n",
    "        optimizer.zero_grad()\n",
    "        z, out = model(batch.x, batch.edge_index)\n",
    "        loss = F.mse_loss(batch.x, out) #F.nll_loss(out[data.train_mask], data.y[data.train_mask])\n",
    "        loss.backward()\n",
    "        torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), 5.)\n",
    "        optimizer.step()"
   ]
  },
